      {
        "paragraph_index": 1,
        "text": "### Chemistry Insight\n\nThe three pKa values correspond to the successive deprotonation of citric acid's three carboxyl groups. The ~1.4–1.3 unit spacing between steps is typical for polycarboxylic acids where the carboxylate groups are close enough to interact electrostatically — each successive proton is harder to remove because the molecule carries increasing negative charge. These values are widely used in buffer preparation (especially the pKa₂ ≈ 4.35 region) and in modeling metal–citrate complexation in biological and environmental systems.\n\n*Source: NIST Standard Reference Database 46 (SRD-46)*",
